06008nam a22006975i 9780824854133DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248541337 a10.1515/97808248541332doi  a(DE-B1597)483878  a(OCoLC)905636932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0210002bisacsh0483pa796qDE-1011 aHavens, Thomas R. H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarathon Japan :bDistance Racing and Civic Culture /cThomas R. H. Havens. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b19 b&w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Culture of Running in Japan -- t2. Racing to Catch Up -- t3. A Galaxy of Distance Runners -- t4. Distance Running as a Commodity -- t5. “Greater Depth, More Women”: Marathons and Ekidens in the 1990s -- t6. From Peak to Plateau: Elite Runners in the 2000s -- t7. Running for Everyone -- tAfterword: Marathon Japan -- tNotes -- tSources Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJapanese have been fervid long-distance runners for many centuries. Today, on a per capita basis, at least as many Japanese residents complete marathons each year as in the United States or any other country. Marathon Japan is the first comprehensive English-language chronicle of the history of this important part of Japanese sports culture. It traces the development of distance racing beginning with the Stockholm Olympics of 1912, when the Japanese government used athletics, and above all the marathon, as a means to continue its late nineteenth-century project of winning the respect of Western countries and achieving parity with the world powers. The marathon soon became the first event in a Western-derived sport in which Japanese proved consistently superior to athletes from other countries. During the 1920s and 1930s, Japanese runners regularly produced the fastest times in the world, and twice in the period after World War Two—in the 1960s and late 1970s–1980s—Japanese men again dominated world marathoning. Japanese women likewise emerged as some of the world's fastest in the 1990s and early 2000s. Meanwhile the general public took up distance running with enthusiasm, starting in the 1960s and continuing unabated today, symbolized most recently by massive open-entry marathons in Tokyo, Osaka, and other Japanese cities comparable in scale and challenge to major world races in Boston, New York, Chicago, London, and Berlin. In this book, Thomas Havens analyzes the origins, development, and significance of Japan's century-long excellence in marathons and long-distance relays (ekiden), as well as the reasons for the explosive growth of distance racing among ordinary citizens in more recent decades. He reveals the key role of commercial media companies in promoting sports, especially marathons and ekidens, from the 1910s to today and explains how running became a consumer commodity beginning in the 1970s as Japanese society matured into an age of capitalist affluence. What comes to light as well are the relentlessly nationalistic goals underlying government policies toward sports—above all marathons, where Japanese have been so successful—throughout the modern era. The public craze for distance racing, both watching and running, has created a shared citizenship of civic participation among young and old, male and female, persons of every social background and level of education. The combination of speedy elite athletes and huge numbers of general-citizen runners means that Japan today is truly a marathon nation. Marathon Japan will appeal to Japan specialists interested in modern cultural and social history. It will engage recreational runners in Japan and abroad as well as anyone interested in the history of sports.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311075236640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485413340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824854133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824854133/original  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-075236-6  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK